        <div class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-red-brand mb-2">Compliance · April 2026 · 12 min read</div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Arlington, TX: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Arlington, Texas, your fire extinguishers aren't just safety equipment — they're a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Arlington Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and local Tarrant County regulations require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Arlington Fire Extinguisher Inspection Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Arlington adopts the International Fire Code (IFC) as its fire prevention code, with local amendments administered through the Arlington Fire Department's Fire Prevention Division. Under this framework, all commercial properties must maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 10 establishes four inspection intervals. Each one matters, and missing any of them puts your business at risk of violations, fines, and — more importantly — leaves your building without reliable fire protection.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">Monthly inspections can be performed by your own staff. The purpose is simple: verify that each extinguisher is in its designated location, accessible (nothing blocking it within 3 feet), the pressure gauge reads in the green zone, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Document each monthly check. While the Arlington Fire Department doesn't always ask for monthly logs during routine inspections, they absolutely will if something goes wrong. A fire incident in a building with no inspection records creates significant liability exposure.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">This is the inspection most people think of — the annual service where a licensed technician inspects each extinguisher and attaches a dated tag. In Texas, the technician must hold a Portable Fire Extinguisher license issued by the Texas Department of Insurance (TDI), State Fire Marshal's Office.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The annual inspection includes checking the mechanical parts, the condition of the extinguishing agent, the operation of the pressure gauge, and the integrity of the hose and nozzle. Any unit that fails the annual inspection must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined. This catches internal corrosion and agent degradation that external inspections can't detect. In the DFW metro climate, where humidity and temperature swings are significant, internal corrosion is more common than building owners expect. The 6-year exam typically includes a complete recharge.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At the 12-year mark, extinguisher cylinders must undergo hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. The cylinder is pressurized well above its normal operating pressure. Units that fail must be condemned and destroyed — they cannot be returned to service. After passing hydrostatic testing, the unit is recharged and returned with a new test date stamped on the cylinder.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Texas-Specific Licensing Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Texas is one of the states that requires specific licensing for fire extinguisher service. Under the Texas Insurance Code, Chapter 6003, any person or company that inspects, services, recharges, or tests portable fire extinguishers must hold a license from the State Fire Marshal's Office. This applies to all four inspection types: annual, 6-year, 12-year, and even fire extinguisher recharging.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">As a property owner or manager in Arlington, you should always verify that your service provider holds a current TDI license. The State Fire Marshal maintains a searchable database of licensed fire protection companies. Using an unlicensed provider doesn't just violate state law — it can void your fire insurance coverage and create massive liability if there's ever a fire incident.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">What the Arlington Fire Department Looks For</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">The Arlington Fire Department's Fire Prevention Division conducts inspections of commercial properties. Their fire inspectors check fire extinguisher compliance as part of routine and complaint-driven inspections. Here's what triggers violations:</p>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-3 mb-8">
          {[
            'Expired inspection tags — the most common violation. If the annual service tag shows a date more than 12 months ago, you\'re out of compliance.',
            'Wrong extinguisher type for the hazard class — Class K units required in commercial kitchens, Class B/C near electrical panels and flammable storage.',
