            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Most service providers in the Arlington area offer volume discounts for properties with 20+ extinguishers. If you manage multiple properties across the DFW metroplex, consolidating your fire extinguisher service with a single provider can reduce per-unit costs by 20–30%.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">NFPA 10 Placement Requirements for Arlington Commercial Properties</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">Getting the right extinguishers inspected means nothing if they're in the wrong locations. NFPA 10 sets maximum travel distances based on hazard classification:</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Class A hazards (ordinary combustibles):</strong> Maximum 75-foot travel distance. This covers most office buildings, retail spaces, and warehouses in Arlington. <strong>Class B hazards (flammable liquids):</strong> Maximum 50-foot travel distance. Applies to auto repair shops, industrial facilities, and storage areas with solvents or fuels. <strong>Class K hazards (cooking oils):</strong> Maximum 30-foot travel distance. Required in every commercial kitchen — restaurants, hospital cafeterias, hotel kitchens, and food truck operations.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Arlington's booming restaurant scene along Division Street, the Entertainment District near AT&T Stadium, and the Viridian and Centreport mixed-use developments mean new commercial kitchens are opening regularly. Each one needs properly placed and inspected Class K extinguishers in addition to standard ABC units.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Tarrant County and Arlington Fire Prevention Contacts</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">If you need to schedule a fire inspection, check on a permit, or get clarification on local fire code requirements:</p>
        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-5 mb-6">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Arlington Fire Department — Fire Prevention Division</strong></p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-1">Address: 515 W. Division Street, Arlington, TX 76011</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-1">Phone: (817) 459-5525</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">The Fire Prevention Division handles plan reviews, inspections, and fire code enforcement for all commercial properties within Arlington city limits.</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mb-2"><strong>Texas State Fire Marshal's Office</strong></p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-1">Licensing verification and complaints: (512) 676-6000</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Verify fire extinguisher service company licensing at the TDI website.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Properties That Require Fire Extinguisher Inspections in Arlington</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">Every commercial property in Arlington is subject to fire extinguisher requirements, but certain property types face more frequent inspections and stricter enforcement:</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Restaurants and food service:</strong> The Entertainment District, Lincoln Square, and the hundreds of restaurants along Cooper Street and Pioneer Parkway are all subject to annual fire inspections that include extinguisher checks. Commercial kitchens also need <a href="/blog/commercial-fire-extinguisher-inspection-guide/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10-compliant extinguishers</a> plus a wet chemical suppression system per NFPA 96.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Multi-family residential:</strong> Apartment complexes and condos in Arlington must maintain extinguishers in common areas, laundry rooms, and near cooking facilities. Properties with more than 16 units often face annual fire department inspections.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Industrial and warehouse:</strong> The Great Southwest Industrial District, one of the largest industrial parks in the DFW area, spans parts of Arlington and Grand Prairie. Warehouses and manufacturing facilities here require extinguishers rated for their specific hazard classes, often including Class B and Class D units for flammable liquids and combustible metals.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Hotels and event venues:</strong> AT&T Stadium, Globe Life Field, the Arlington Convention Center, and the surrounding hotel district all require comprehensive fire extinguisher coverage and are subject to rigorous annual inspections due to high-occupancy classifications.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Office buildings and retail:</strong> The Centerpoint and Highlands developments, along with the many strip centers along I-20 and Highway 360, need standard Class A/B/C extinguisher coverage with proper travel distance compliance.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Penalties for Non-Compliance in Arlington, TX</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">The consequences of failing a fire extinguisher inspection in Arlington are real and escalating:</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>First violation:</strong> Notice of Violation with a correction period (typically 30 days). No fine if corrected promptly.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Repeat or uncorrected violations:</strong> Fines starting at $500 per violation per day. Multiple extinguisher issues can compound quickly — a building with 15 non-compliant extinguishers could face $7,500 per day in cumulative fines.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Serious violations:</strong> The fire marshal has authority to issue a stop-work order or vacate order for buildings with egregious fire safety deficiencies. This is rare but does happen, particularly in buildings that have ignored multiple notices.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">How to Stay Compliant: A Simple Maintenance Schedule</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3">The easiest way to avoid violations is to set up a maintenance schedule and stick to it:</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Every month:</strong> Walk the building and visually check every extinguisher. Takes 5 minutes per floor for most properties. Log the date and any issues found.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Every 12 months:</strong> Schedule professional inspection with a TDI-licensed fire protection company. They'll inspect, tag, and document every unit. Budget $15–$35 per extinguisher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-3"><strong>Every 6 years:</strong> Internal examination of stored-pressure units. Your service company should track this based on manufacture dates. Budget $25–$55 per unit.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4"><strong>Every 12 years:</strong> Hydrostatic testing. Again, your service company should track manufacture dates and flag units approaching the 12-year mark. Budget $30–$75 per unit. Some units may need replacement instead of testing — factor in $45–$95 per replacement unit.</p>

